{
  "title": "Intraoperative Vital Sign Trajectories and Acute Kidney Injury After Pancreaticoduodenectomy",
  "abstract": "Importance: Pancreaticoduodenectomy (PD) is a complex operation with substantial intraoperative hemodynamic variation. Threshold-based monitoring of individual variables may not adequately capture coordinated physiological changes during surgery.\n\nObjective: To identify physiological subtypes using dynamic time warping (DTW) clustering of multivariate intraoperative vital signs and to examine their association with postoperative acute kidney injury (AKI).\n\nDesign: Retrospective cohort study at a tertiary academic medical center in Sendai, Japan. Consecutive patients who underwent PD between April 2014 and March 2024.\n\nResults: Among 666 patients, 4 subclusters were identified: SC1 (n=247), SC2 (n=156), SC3 (n=147), and SC4 (n=116). AKI incidence differed across subclusters (SC1, 6.1%; SC2, 14.1%; SC3, 7.5%; SC4, 5.2%; P=.02). SC2 had higher odds of AKI than SC1 (adjusted OR, 2.70 [95% CI, 1.34-5.45]; P=.005).\n\nConclusions: DTW clustering of intraoperative multivariate vital signs identified 4 physiological subtypes. A subtype characterized by tachycardia, higher mean arterial pressure, and lower urine output had higher odds of postoperative AKI. These findings support trajectory-based perioperative phenotyping as a potentially useful approach for postoperative risk stratification.",
